content.title: [Draft] PM. Playbook
content.visibleText:
3. Pick the Playbook

Goal: Ensure timely exploration and actionable feedback for the site.

Strategy: With all new products on the same, present product customers tend to ignore emails from our new solutions until the media campaign ends. Explore solutions.

Problems:

Control is shared across departments and we can rarely sway the lead build. mission. Users told us they prefer to receive more frequent and more informative updates about our product line during the year. However, the "set-it-and-forget-it" strategy is longer than their attention span.

PM is responsible for setting the approach that best balances the cost of delivering value vs. it should try to engage customers until the site is up.

- Should focus more on "outreach" than "exploration." Delivery-first engagement cycle or another cycle to be managed?

- Can customers remain engaged with good insights or "bites" for team boosting and morale?

- How can we ensure responsible on-site customer engagement for immediate, even when launching features of the site?

Inception Playbook

- The feature has not started developments, we are in the future strategy or feature planning stage.

- Goal: Ensure user and deeper affiliation with customer interactions, and by meeting their precise engagement focus on customer research.

- Must involve customer engagement with Customer Feedback Reports.

Development Playbook

- Fastest in its development, we can work with wireframes, full designs, rough prototypes.

- Goal: Better wire framing during development by testing and interacting with customers.

- Must involve Customer Feedback Reports.

Early Engagement Playbook

- The feature was developed and released

- Goal: Ensure timely exploration and actionable feedback for the site.
